replies.text:
@davidblyth5495 I lived for a few years with a wind pump or wind motor as I like to think. That bore was only 30 metres deep but the owner put it in the wrong place against my advice. My preference was the opposite side of the 10 metre high church that he owned and he wanted to put it near the front. The opposite side to the where the prevailing wind came from. The wind would spiral and eddy as it came over the high roof causing the poor mill blades, even when turned off, to turn one way, then the other, then rotate on it's vertical axis, back the other way, then the blades would do the same again. Very disturbing to watch in a high wind, it was creaking and groaning all the time. A few tower top repairs later, it destroyed itself by fracturing a tower support and dumping or rather, hinging the head until it rested against the remaining tower.
But... the power was awesome. We'd cast a large block of concrete at the base where the pipe was anchored off, and I've seen it lift that block several inches off the ground in a good wind from any other direction!!
We also changed the steel pipes for a single length of poly pipe. The elasticity of it made for less strain in the head and easier to raise.
